<DOC><DOCNO> AP900801-0177 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-90 1903EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Sunbathers     08-01 0189</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Bush-Sunbathers,190</SECOND><HEAD>Tourists Surprised by Jogging President</HEAD><HEAD>LaserPhoto WX21</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two young women sunbathing alongside thePotomac River didn't bat an eye Wednesday when President Bush andhis entourage jogged right by them.   Bush appreciatively eyed the women, smiled and apologized,``You're on national television, ladies. Sorry about that!''   Bikini-clad Dana Habeck, 22, of San Luis Obispo, Calif., andLinda Kreider, 33, of Philadelphia, who wore a one-piece suit,laughed and told reporters they didn't mind the attention.   ``It's great,'' said Ms. Kreider.   The pair was soaking up the sun at the isolated eastern end ofHain's Point in East Potomac Park on the banks of the Potomac Riverwhen Bush came jogging by with Secret Service agents and severalrunning partners, including Rep. Larry Hopkins, R-Ky., and BritHume, a White House correspondent for ABC News.   The president, wearing shorts and a Houston Police DepartmentT-shirt, got in 2{ miles on a sunny afternoon.   Hopkins told reporters later that he had already jogged fourmiles Wednesday morning when he got the invitation to run with thepresident. He decided not to pass up the opportunity.</TEXT></DOC>